B13^Representing strategic play^^^^^^^Based on these early observations it appears that microworlds of the tactical and strategic modes do not compete between themselves in the same sense as do microworlds of the tactical cluster but are distinct alternatives between which a choice is made.  Since the choice is based upon preferences more than upon contextual circumstances, we represent them as in Figure 4, where preference for strategic play is represented as choking off the output of the tactical microworld cluster.  Note also, based on Miriam's failure to block Robby's threat in game 2.3, that the Corners world's choking of the tactical output operated without any interruption from the Block world.  Further, from the reaction in game 2.4, we note Miriam was quite reluctant to back off from her committment to strategic play to tactical play.  The evidence we have seen of other influences on this bias, Miriam's avoiding strategic play while opposing Robby, is represented as an inhibition on the output of the strategic cluster dependent upon the identity of her opponent.  This completes the initial characterization of Miriam's Tic tac toe related structures at the beginning of The Intimate Study.  This initial model will be modified and developed based on the material of succeeding sections. 

